Introduction

This text mining project embarks on an extensive exploration of the narrative intricacies and thematic richness of L.M. Montgomery’s “The Blue Castle” and “Anne of Green Gables.” Montgomery, a pivotal figure in Canadian literature, is renowned for her vivid depictions of Prince Edward Island’s landscapes and the emotionally resonant stories of characters navigating the complexities of early 20th-century life. Her novels, widely celebrated for their depth of character and emotional insight, offer fertile terrain for a detailed linguistic and thematic analysis.

This project aims to systematically uncover patterns of word usage, sentiments, and character relationships that underpin Montgomery’s narrative techniques and thematic priorities. The analysis focuses on identifying how specific word choices and the frequency of these words contribute to the development of the novels’ themes such as personal identity, social conformity, and emotional resilience. Furthermore, sentiment analysis will highlight the emotional undertones across the novels, providing insights into how Montgomery uses language to evoke feelings and forge connections with her readers.

By mapping out the most common bigrams—pairs of words that frequently appear adjacent to each other—the study will also shed light on the dynamic interactions between characters, revealing underlying social structures and individual character arcs. This analytical approach not only enhances our understanding of Montgomery’s stylistic choices but also deepens our appreciation of how her narrative strategies reflect and respond to the societal norms and challenges of her era.

Moreover, this project will compare and contrast the themes and emotional landscapes of both novels to discern any shifts in Montgomery’s narrative focus and thematic exploration over time. This comparative analysis will offer a broader perspective on her literary evolution and the historical contexts that shaped her writing.

Through this extensive textual analysis, the project aims to contribute valuable insights to academic discussions about Montgomery’s literary legacy, providing a richer understanding of her contributions to not only Canadian literature but also to the depiction of complex social and personal themes through the art of storytelling.

Montgomery: The Blue Castle and Anne of Green Gables. Data Cleaning and Preparation

In the data cleaning and preparation phase of my text mining project, I employ the tidytext package, specifically using the unnest_tokens function to break down the text of L.M. Montgomery’s novels into individual words, or tokens. This step transforms each row of text into separate rows for each word in the new dataframe, referred to here as tidy_Montgomery. Following tokenization, I utilize an anti_join function to remove common stop words, which are typically frequent but carry little unique textual significance, thus focusing the analysis on more meaningful words. After cleaning, a frequency count of the remaining words is performed using dplyr::count, sorting the results to identify the most prevalent terms. The result is a tibble displaying the frequency of each word, with ‘anne’, ‘valancy’, and ‘marilla’ appearing as some of the most frequent words, indicating their significance in the narratives of “Anne of Green Gables” and “The Blue Castle”. This methodical approach ensures that the analysis is concentrated on the text’s most impactful elements.

tidy_Montgomery <- Montgomery %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words)
## Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
#stop_words
tidy_Montgomery %>%
  dplyr::count(word, sort = TRUE)

Data Analysis

Frequency Analysis

In the frequency analysis stage of my project, I conducted a thorough examination of the most common words found in L.M. Montgomery’s novels, specifically focusing on The Blue Castle and Anne of Green Gables. After removing stop words—which are commonly used words that offer little value in the way of context or differentiation—the data was processed to highlight the most frequently occurring terms. The analysis revealed that words like “Anne,” “Valancy,” and “Marilla” are among the most frequent, indicating their central roles in the narratives.

To refine the analysis further, I filtered out contractions and common verbal phrases such as “I’m,” “don’t,” and “it’s,” which, despite their high frequency, do not provide significant insights into the thematic or narrative structure of the texts. The remaining words were then counted and sorted to identify the top 20, which were visualized using a bar chart with the words listed in descending order of frequency. This visualization not only illustrates the prominence of character names but also highlights terms that potentially signify key themes or elements within Montgomery’s work, such as “time,” “girl,” “eyes,” and “home.” This methodological approach offers a clear view of the linguistic patterns in Montgomery’s writing, shedding light on the characters and themes that dominate her novels.

v=c("i’m","don’t","it’s","didn’t","i’ve","i’ll","i’d","isn’t","can’t") 
tidy_Montgomery %>%
  dplyr::count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  filter(n > 167) %>%
  filter(!word%in%v) %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(word, n)) +
  geom_col() +
  xlab(NULL) +
  coord_flip() + ggtitle("The top 20 Most Common Words in L.M.Montgomerys' Novels")

Sentiment in L.M. Montgomery’ Two Novels

tidytext package contains several sentiment lexicons, I am using “bing” for the following tasks.

In the sentiment analysis section of my text mining project on L.M. Montgomery’s novels The Blue Castle and Anne of Green Gables, I utilized the tidytext package, which provides access to multiple sentiment lexicons. For this specific analysis, I chose the “bing” due to its binary classification of words into positive and negative sentiments.

bing_word_counts <- tidy_Montgomery %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
  dplyr::count(word, sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>%
  ungroup()

The sentiment analysis process involved joining the tokenized text data with “bing” using the inner_join function. The resultant data frame, bing_word_counts, provided a detailed count of words associated with each sentiment category.

bing_word_counts %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  top_n(10) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(word, n, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sentiment, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(y = "Words Contribute to sentiment",
       x = NULL) +
  coord_flip()
## Selecting by n

Analysis of the sentiment data revealed that “miss” and “love” were the most frequent negative and positive words, respectively. “Miss” often appeared in contexts reflecting societal pressures or personal challenges, particularly those faced by unmarried women, which are recurring themes in Montgomery’s novels. In contrast, “love” frequently appeared in scenarios depicting romance and personal affection, underscoring the positive relationships that are central to Montgomery’s narratives.

Bigram Analysis

In my project on L.M. Montgomery’s The Blue Castle and Anne of Green Gables, I conducted a bigram analysis to explore common word pairings across the texts. This involved using the unnest_tokens function from the tidytext package to generate bigrams, which are pairs of adjacent words in the text. After initially extracting these bigrams, I applied additional cleaning to remove stop words and unnecessary elements, refining the dataset to focus on the most meaningful and frequent bigrams.

Montgomery_bigrams <- Montgomery %>%
  unnest_tokens(bigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 2)

library(tidyr)
bigrams_separated <- Montgomery_bigrams %>%
  separate(bigram, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ")
bigrams_filtered <- bigrams_separated %>%
  filter(!word1 %in% stop_words$word) %>%
  filter(!word2 %in% stop_words$word)
bigram_counts <- bigrams_filtered %>% 
  dplyr::count(word1, word2, sort = TRUE)

Conclusions

The analysis of L.M. Montgomery’s “The Blue Castle” and “Anne of Green Gables” through advanced text mining techniques has provided a deeper insight into Montgomery’s literary craftsmanship and thematic exploration. By examining word frequency, sentiment analysis, and the relational dynamics between characters via bigrams, this project has highlighted the intricate ways in which Montgomery constructs her narratives and embeds deeper meanings within her texts.

The frequency analysis revealed a rich tapestry of language that Montgomery uses to draw readers into her settings and experiences. The most commonly used words and phrases often pertained to elements of nature, emotional states, and social interactions, underscoring her ability to weave complex emotional and environmental threads into her storytelling. This lexical choice not only enhances the immersive quality of her narratives but also reflects the intense personal and societal conflicts faced by her characters.

Sentiment analysis further illustrated how Montgomery adeptly balances positive and negative emotions to create compelling narrative arcs. Words carrying positive sentiments frequently associated with themes of love, hope, and resilience, which are central to Montgomery’s narratives, highlighted her optimistic view of life’s potential. Conversely, the prevalence of negatively connotated words around themes such as isolation and societal pressure emphasized the challenges her characters must navigate, providing a realistic portrayal of the struggles inherent in personal growth and social acceptance.

The examination of bigrams exposed the significant relationships and social structures that are crucial to Montgomery’s plots. The interactions between characters, as depicted through their linked mentions, reveal not only personal relationships but also the broader social fabric of the communities she describes. These relationships are pivotal in shaping the protagonists’ journeys and are meticulously crafted to underscore the themes of belonging and identity.

In conclusion, this project has not only affirmed the enduring relevance of L.M. Montgomery’s work but has also showcased the potential of text mining in uncovering new layers of interpretation in classic literature. Montgomery’s novels, through their complex interplay of characters, themes, and linguistic choices, continue to offer valuable insights into the human condition and the transformative power of narrative. This analytical approach has opened up fresh avenues for appreciating Montgomery’s contribution to literature and has provided a quantitative backing to the qualitative aspects traditionally explored in literary studies.
